===Etymology===
{{etyl|enm}} {{term|see|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|sæ|sǣ|lang=ang|sea, lake}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|saiwiz|lang=gem-pro}} (compare West Frisian {{term|see|lang=fy}}, Dutch {{term|zee|lang=nl}}, German {{term|See|lang=de}}), probably from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{recons|sh₂ei-u̯o|lang=ine-pro}}- 'to be fierce, afflict' (compare Latin {{term|saevus|lang=la||wild, fierce}}, Tocharian {{term|saiwe|lang=txb||itch}}, Latvian {{term|sievs|lang=lt}}, {{term|sivs|sīvs|lang=lt|sharp, biting}}).<ref>Vladimir Orel, ''A Handbook of Germanic Etymology'', s.v. "saiwiz" (Louden, Netherlands: Brill, 2003), 314.</ref> More to [[sore]].

